name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gdomv"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcom"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Society/Community</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gdomv"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcrim"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Crime/Legal Action</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gdomv"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gsoc"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Social Issues</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gdomv"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Top of the News</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Why It Matters; Early help for troubled kids</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>A student's problems often stem from problems at home. The parents could be fighting, there might be no money to pay the bills or worse, there could be domestic violence. The student then gets depressed and finds it hard to concentrate in class. Some become angry and defiant. Some play truant.</Para><Para>To effectively help the child, it is key to uncover what is happening at home and address those problems. Hence, a system which guides schools to identify and refer students who need help to resources in the community is invaluable.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>With their parents' consent, the children - and their families - can be referred to a family service centre (FSC), which provides counselling and other aid, or to a social service office, which administers financial aid schemes. The FSC's social workers will then work with the family to tackle the problems.</Para><Para>The referral protocol, piloted in end 2014, has been introduced in 208 schools so far.</Para><Para>It will be rolled out in all primary and secondary schools and junior colleges under the Ministry of Education's (MOE) purview by the end of the year.</Para><Para>Minister for Social and Family Development Desmond Lee highlighted this referral system during the debate on his ministry's budget earlier this month. This system is a result of the ministry and the MOE coming together to boost support for children from vulnerable families, who may face a host of problems and need help from multiple agencies.</Para><Para>Without action on the part of the schools, these problems would have remained hidden. And without the resources of the various help agencies working together, it would be harder to tackle them.</Para><Para>Last year, schools referred about 900 cases to FSCs and social service offices. Social workers interviewed say the referral system helps to detect and address the problems that students face earlier.</Para><Para>This improves the chances of nipping the problem in the bud. It also gives these children, who might otherwise have drifted into deeper trouble, a fighting chance at a brighter future.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Theresa Tan </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

